In article <1993Oct28.145301.11233@ncsu.edu> rerodd@eos.ncsu.edu writes:

>
>RIPEM??  Doesn't that thing use DES?  DES is no good because chips have been
>developed that will break a key overnight for ~$1M.  It will be a mistake if
>an already dead cryptosystem is deployed on the internet.

True, but irrelevant.  DES breaking machines allow a DES key to be
determined from a {plaintext, ciphertext} pair.  This is irrelevant
to any system which uses RSA for key exchange because the DES key is
changed for every message.  Thus, by the time you have a key it's no
use to you.

Andrew.

